onflict, Perrillo uncovers the ways they have become so, brought about both by teachers who have come to see civil rights efforts as detracting from or competing with their own goals and by civil rights activists whose aims have de-professionalized the role of the educator. Focusing in particular on unionized teachers, Perrillo finds a new vantage point from which to examine the relationship between school and community, showing how in this struggle, educators, activists, and especially our students have lost out.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxEducationxHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aAfrican AmericansxEducationzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights movementsxHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aCivil rights movementszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aEducationxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aEducation. 0aEducational equalizationxHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aEducational equalizationzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacism in educationxHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aRacism in educationzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aTeachersxCivil rightsxHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aTeachersxCivil rightszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aTeachersxPolitical activityxHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aTeachersxPolitical activityzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aTeachers' unionsxHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aTeachers' unionszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z97831106387